== STANDARD PROCEDURES

Once you're officially admitted, you'll move to a labor room. Here's what typically happens in the first hour or so:

=== Paperwork

Even if you pre-registered, there's usually more paperwork at admission. This includes:

- _Consent forms_ for treatment, procedures, and potential emergencies
- _Reviewing your birth preferences_ with the admitting nurse
- _Insurance and identification verification_
- _Signing HIPAA privacy forms_
- _Contact information_ for your emergency contact

_Pro tip:_ Pre-register around 36 weeks! Most hospitals let you complete forms ahead of time, either online or in person. This dramatically reduces the paperwork you'll deal with while having contractions.

=== IV Placement or Hep Lock

Most hospitals want IV access established when you're admitted. This might be:

_A full IV line:_ A needle placed in your hand or arm, connected to tubing and a bag of fluids that continuously drip into your body.

_A hep lock (saline lock):_ The same needle placement, but capped off instead of connected to fluids. It gives them quick access if needed but doesn't tether you to an IV pole.

Why do they want this?
- Quick access for medications if needed
- Ability to give fluids if you become dehydrated
- Emergency access if complications arise
- Required if you want an epidural

See our #link(<ch-iv-hep-lock>)[IV vs Hep Lock chapter] for more on this decision.

=== Fetal Monitoring Strip

You'll have the same monitoring belts from triage placed again. The initial strip usually lasts 20-30 minutes and establishes a "baseline" for how your baby is doing.

_Continuous monitoring_ means wearing the belts throughout labor. Many hospitals default to this.

_Intermittent monitoring_ means checking baby's heart rate periodically (often every 15-30 minutes in active labor) rather than constantly.

See our #link(<ch-fetal-monitoring>)[Fetal Monitoring chapter] for a deeper dive.

=== Cervical Check

The admitting nurse or provider will typically do a cervical exam to establish where you are in labor. As mentioned above, this will be uncomfortable — it involves a gloved hand reaching into the vaginal canal to feel the cervix, and during labor when everything is already sensitive and tight, it can be quite painful. It's usually quick (under a minute), but knowing that ahead of time helps you prepare mentally. Ask your nurse to wait until you're between contractions if possible, and focus on slow breathing through it.

They're checking:

- _Dilation:_ How open your cervix is (measured 0-10 centimeters)
- _Effacement:_ How thin your cervix has become (measured as a percentage)
- _Station:_ How far baby has descended into your pelvis (-3 to +3)
- _Position:_ Which way baby is facing

*A note on infection risk:* Every cervical check introduces a small risk of infection, and this risk goes up significantly if your water has already broken #citation[1]#citation[2]#citation[3]#citation[4]. Once membranes have ruptured, the protective barrier between the outside world and your baby is gone, and each exam can potentially introduce bacteria. This is one reason to be thoughtful about how many cervical checks you consent to — especially after your water breaks. You can always ask, "Is this check necessary right now, or can we wait?"

=== Vital Signs

Your blood pressure, temperature, pulse, and oxygen levels will be checked. These are typically repeated every 1-4 hours throughout labor depending on your situation.

