== PRO TIPS

=== Making Admission Go Smoothly

_Before you leave home:_
- Confirm you're really in labor (call the hospital line if unsure)
- Have bags packed and by the door
- Eat a light snack if you can (you may not eat again for a while)
- Put on comfortable clothes easy to change out of
- Bring your ID and insurance card somewhere accessible

_Pre-registration makes everything easier._ Seriously. Do it around 36 weeks.

_Bring multiple copies of your birth plan._ Nurses change shifts, and you may see different providers.

_Arrive during the right stage of labor._ You may have heard of the "4-1-1 rule" — contractions 4 minutes apart, lasting 1 minute, for 1 hour. This book advocates the *3-1-1 rule* instead: contractions 3 minutes apart, lasting 1 minute, for 1 hour. See our #link(<ch-when-to-go>)[Stages of Labor chapter] for why we recommend the 3-1-1 rule. Coming too early often means being sent home, but don't wait too long either.

_Bring your own pillow._ It's more comfortable, smells like home, and instantly makes the room feel more yours. Put it in a colorful pillowcase so it doesn't get mixed up with hospital linens.

_Know the parking situation._ Where is the drop-off? Where does your partner park? Is there a cost? Figure this out ahead of time.

_Have phone chargers ready._ Labor can be long. Dead phones are the last thing you need.

_Wear your own labor gown if you want._ Hospital gowns are free and functional, but many women prefer their own birthing gowns. Just know it might get messy.

=== The Words That Open Doors

When you want something:
- "Is it possible to...?"
- "I'd prefer to try..."
- "Can we talk about alternatives?"
- "What would you recommend?"

When you need time:
- "Can I have a few minutes to think about this?"
- "My partner and I need to discuss this privately."
- "Is this urgent or can we revisit it in an hour?"

When declining:
- "I understand, and I'd like to decline for now."
- "I'd prefer to wait on that. Can we reassess later?"
- "Thank you for the recommendation. I've decided to..."

=== Things Nurses Wish Patients Knew

- _They want you to have a good experience too._ Most nurses went into this field because they love helping families through birth.
- _Clear communication helps everyone._ Tell them what you need instead of hoping they guess.
- _Shift change happens._ Don't take it personally when your nurse leaves. Get to know the new one.
- _They've seen it all._ Nothing you do will shock or embarrass them.
- _Flexibility goes both ways._ When you're flexible with them, they're often more flexible with you.

